{"id":"1301.1579","submitter":"Habibollah Razmi","authors":"S. Y. Rokni, H. Razmi, and M. R. Bordbar","title":"The Gott-Kaiser-Stebbins (GKS) Effect in an Accelerated Expanding\n  Universe","comments":"9 pages, Accepted for publication in Iranian Journal of Astronomy and\n  Astrophysics","journal-ref":"Iranian Journal of Astronomy and Astrophysics, Vol. 2, No. 2,\n  121-125 (2015)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We want to find the cosmological constant influence on cosmic microwave\nbackground (CMB) temperature due to moving linear cosmic strings. Considering\nthe space-time metric of a linear cosmic string in an accelerated expanding\nuniverse, the Gott-Kaiser-Stebbins (GKS) effect, as an important mechanism in\nproducing temperature discontinuity in the CMB, is considered and its\nmodification due to the effect of the cosmological constant is calculated. The\nresult shows that a positive cosmological constant (i.e. the presence of cosmic\nstrings in an accelerated expanding universe) weakens the discontinuity in\ntemperature so that more strong resolution is needed to detect the\ncorresponding influences on the CMB power spectrum and anisotropy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Dec 2012 11:37:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 31 Aug 2015 11:22:07 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 18 Oct 2015 20:07:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-20"}
